ut also significantly broadens the scope of recent debates in postcolonial feminist theory to account for the Spanish empire and its (former) colonies. Organized into three sections: colonialism and women's migrations; race, performance, and colonial ideologies; and gender and colonialism in literary and political debates, Unsettling Colonialism brings together the work of nine scholars. Given its interdisciplinary approach and accessible style, the book will appeal to both specialists in nineteenth-century Iberian and Latin American studies and a broader audience of scholars in gender, cultural, transatlantic, transpacific, postcolonial, and empire studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aGender identity in literature. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aSex in literature. 0aSpanish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aArea Studies : Hispanic Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh1 aChang, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMateos, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, N. Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, N. Michelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSoria, Mar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSurwillo, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTolliver, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsuchiya, Akiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsuchiya, Akiko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go